While almost any mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can still make phone calls.
So, of course, it looks like it’s better to just buy a phone.
However, there are plenty of reasons why you should play an independent player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the claims of the future owner.
It’s hard to buy a great expensive record player at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc’s latest album.
Once such musical novelties do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this either.
However, if you have LPs with art rock, jazz or blues on the shelf, you’re probably dreaming of at least one.
This is also the case with music while traveling, i.e. with compressed music, expressed in a simplified way - music in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For one, it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, but a Pink-Floyd fan will probably hardly be able to buy headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide-ranging.
The battery life is also crucial.
Some good music players can play much more than just music, but what mobile phones can do, they don’t even make sense.
No modern device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, the phone and the Sims, it can play music and videos, record both, it sometimes has a better, sometimes a worse camera, and maybe even navigate.
And if you still include the smartphones and communicators, you have almost a small computer in your pocket.
