The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe it won’t wait long.
That the Czech mobile service providers are among the most expensive in Europe at all, we have already reported on Mobil.cz many times.
By the way, this was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which noted that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the regulation of roaming charges, there is likely to be a paradox - for some customers of Czech mobile providers, text messages from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices so high in the Czech Republic compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really makes a battle announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile operators like to complain that there is an extreme amount of competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, who had often stated in the past that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with its own network will no longer have a lot of chances (by the way, it would probably hardly find any frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile phone market resulted in a significant price reduction, which the classic mobile phone providers then had to react to.
Prior to the entry into the market of companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar votes in the UK as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don’t have to look for examples for long.
In February we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider succeeded in attracting more than 100 thousand customers and thus rising to the fifth largest provider in the country.
Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to work effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a classic provider.
You do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, the virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies – they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offering.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to put on a non-clichic target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operating company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept could be found in the Czech Republic as well as in Poland.
Vodafone Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>’s press spokesperson also doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offering."
In the Czech Republic, the mobile phone providers think
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile phone provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobileking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look particularly hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries of our region,” says Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, a press spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
For some time now, your interest in launching a virtual mobile service provider has been shown by the GTS Novela group, which wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the area of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only landline, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile service providers.
With some of them, we were already able to achieve negotiation progress,” said Pavel Kaidl, the group’s spokesman.
Maybe better times are coming.
Non-official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has great specifics compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area", says in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the press department of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2.
The specifics of the Czech market also point to other providers.
T-Mobile press secretary Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds, in rare agreement with O2’s statement: “We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on.”
And she adds, "T-Mobile's network will hardly see a virtual provider until the end of the year.
At this moment we would have to have a concrete offer in order to be able to think in such a short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we see as the best from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet.”
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
The approach of mobile providers is easy to understand, another provider called more competition, this would lead to lower prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
Why, then, should such a competitor be made easier to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull on a string when it comes to something also proves the long way back and forth about the creation of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure in the direction of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was at the time when U:fon came onto the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This also proves the publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
Now U:fon is an argument as to why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has recently also been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile phone provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, its services."
However, given this approach of mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
It is exclusively owned by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem his very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile operator would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual operator on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential prospects was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," said Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS External Relations Department in his response to our request.
Such a formulation would not be surprising by representatives of the providers.
This is more than a matter of concern from an authority representing consumer interests and, among other things, ensuring that no one abuses their position on the market.
In particular, when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: “Regardless of where virtual providers work normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile phone services.”
However, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not among the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
In this case, the almost touching harmony of the three mobile providers, which results from their reactions, is really shocking.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the price of petrol at the gas stations is certainly just coincidence and the result of a fierce competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs in this matter that indicate an act directed against competition, and therefore has no reason to intervene in the matter in any way.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so they also do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile phone market for virtual providers are likely to be missing from the regulatory authority for telecommunications,” Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile providers has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - for the market entry of a virtual provider, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile service provider has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily assumes a dominant position in a particular segment.
Even if one does not agree with this argument, it should at least be a warning to the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile providers are acting remarkably similarly.
Complaints by a number of interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novela) prove that they encounter very similar obstacles when negotiating with all providers.
The removal of responsibility to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act did not achieve the extension of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS need to know all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay when no one's looking
First of all, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
It is companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but they are only partially public.
These are usually companies that operate in the area of multi-level marketing.
Own mobile phone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies are usually only available to selected companies.
The joke of the matter is that the company acts towards the operator as a classic corporate customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he will then receive special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile service providers prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a breach of the contractual terms with which we will then deal, which can lead to the termination of cooperation with the relevant company," answered Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> on our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not speak to the operators of the mobile phone providers.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such a procedure.
As a result of the activities of these companies, they do not receive negligible profits, but at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite the fact that the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card on their phone is not running on their name, so they can’t fully dispose of it like the normal customers of the mobile phone providers.”
But that alone would have to be at least strange.
There is also another question for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile providers close their eyes before such a procedure, why are they locking themselves against a virtual provider?
It is to be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has quite strong competences for the detection of such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to satisfy itself with the explanation of the providers, they do not know anything about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been emphasised several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers resulted in a significant price drop in the various services.
In virtually all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the traditional providers have tried to prevent their emergence more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small or too saturated a market, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies intervened at these moments, which were not trying to safeguard the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Be it through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and that followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing themselves at the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in the competences in these cases is more than favorable.
But let us not throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon emerges, the Czech mobile phone market may soon set in motion again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (to discriminate against) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally not be more expensive to make phone calls than the rest of Europe.
