The Sudeten demanded a U.S. referendum
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans had asked for the incorporation of the Bohemian Forest into the United States.
This is evident from a letter that is stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the auspices of the United States of America.
With such a wish, in 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the US president.
This can be seen, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
In the letter, the Germans of Krumau asked the American president not to allow the return of the "Sudetengau" - which was taken on the basis of the Munich agreement by Hitler - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units do not enter as oppressors and enemies of German territory, but as liberators," the letter reads, which is signed with the words "people whose fate lies at the heart of the Sudetes".
Since the connection to Czechoslovakia makes the Sudeten Germans suspect, knowing the Czech national character, that they would expect brutality, ruthlessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take over the protection of the Bohemian Forest for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that without regard to the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants of this area, you are addressing a foreign state that is trying to suppress and eliminate minorities and has contributed nothing at all to the victory of the Allies," the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is supposedly the fear of revenge from the “Czech oppressors”.
If the President of the United States had doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he initiated a referendum in the Bohemian Forestgau on whether the inhabitants wanted to become part of the United States or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat na<0xC3><0xAF>ve in today’s knowledge of post-war history, it does, in the opinion of some contemporary witnesses, draw a good picture of the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
Even though the Bohemian Germans had to at least suspect that they would negotiate on their deportation from the Republic, few of them admitted such a possibility at all.
Some were waiting for the United States and Britain to negotiate some sort of autonomy for the Sudetes.
Others thought they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
It also confirms the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
