Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits associated almost always with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and in the execution/control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in the rest of the primates and seems to be lacking entirely in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to assume that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic characteristic is probably in the linguistic nature of man: Since such a large part of his experience is associated with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
