But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly affect it, so animal consciousness, as it may be, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it cannot be measured nor, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then his research presents us with great problems.
Most of my remarks relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be scientifically more easily accessible.
One could examine the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their contents, and this is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But with this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, one focuses more on the neural correlates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
