“The main concern of Avalon Bay is to renovate this dilapidated alley and make it a public meeting place,” she said, adding that the city itself had proposed the sale.
Seth Donlin, spokesman for the Department of Building Protection, said it was actually the city’s desire to sell the street, stressing that the department’s job was to develop the real estate rather than manage it.
Compared to its colorful neighborhood The Bowery, Extra Place has retained some of its historical impression.
Some believe that the road got its name in 1802 when a large farm belonging to Philip Minthorne was divided between his numerous children and a narrow strip of land was not claimed by anyone.
The back door of the music club CBGB, the punk rock monument, which was closed in 2006, opened to the Extra Place and the street is probably best known as a backdrop for the photo on the cover of Ramones' album "Rocket to Russia".
The patch was great, said Danny Fields, the manager of the Ramones, who had taken the photo in November 1976.
The road was full of scrap, rags and parts of barrels, posters, leaves and ropes.
Some residents, including the bloggers who write about the gentrification of the East Village, have rejected the idea of selling Extra Place, arguing that this public property, as modest as it is, should continue to remain public.
Others have praised Extra Place as a rarity – a virtually unchanged splinter of the city that should be left alone.
Jeremiah Moss, who runs the blog called "Jeremiah's Disappearing New York" (subtitled "The Book of Complaints: A Bitter Nostalgic Look at the Extinct City"), has published part of the conversation of the city's history about Extra Place, which had appeared in the 1952 magazine "The New Yorker".
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote at the time: "Extra Place is a small narrow dead end that remains dark even during the day and is characterized by rusted metal doors of warehouses, closed windows and by rain gutters flying past weekly newspapers".
With a few exceptions, the road looked just like it was recently in an evening.
A rat ran through the back of the road, not far from the door that used to lead to the CBGB, where today there is a more expensive clothing store.
Graffiti was seen on the walls and an empty beer bottle lay on the floor not far from a fresh bunch of out-of-the-box newspapers.
Some passers-by said they had rarely thought about Extra Place, but suggested that the road could be polished up a bit.
Fields, added that in his opinion, some people underestimate the appeal of the road in its current state.
The best years of my life, he said, were in the places that were dark, damp and disgusting.
Debate on bilingual education: Education in an English-speaking environment
In this issue of the Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior research associate in Kaliphonic Studies and senior director in the Department of Educational Sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as good as you think: Why the middle class needs a school selection".
Addressing Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentions that “the probability of successful completion of school with African-American and Hispanic students is lower than with white students” — which is true.
To close this gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends a bilingual transition phase in education for those who first learn English.
Still, the question to Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Take as an example "Sixth Street Prep", a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently been in the country, learn English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, an astonishing 100 percent of fourth-grade students passed the state exam in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of the children from the fourth year of school were rated good in the English exam.
This amazing success was achieved by other methods than those favored by Obama.
Sixth Street School puts its emphasis on review and practice, on constant control of knowledge and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
Furthermore, the school practices the approach by which education takes place in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly the point that Obama should take into account, says head of the school, Linda Mikels.
This approach places emphasis on the almost exclusive use of the English language in specialist teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school had a remarkable success with a student who had just come from Mexico. 12 months later, one would enter the classroom and no longer be able to recognize him.
"It works," she remarked, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like the "Sixth Street Prep" as a model for other schools with a large proportion of Latin American and other English learning students?
The school’s achievements would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational positions within its own party (the national educational associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and its own consistent support of bilingual education make predictions about Obama’s response uncertain.
While agreeing to the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about the legislation targeting “English only.”
Instead, he said, “You should make sure your child can speak Spanish.”
If Obama actually wants to close the performance gap, he should carefully consider educational models that work rather than despise and trivialize them.
