After prices peaked at $145.29 per barrel in July, they dropped to almost $90 per barrel this month, then again, as a result of the huge uncertainty in financial markets.
On Monday, investors showed concern again, although congressional representatives had announced that they had agreed on a rescue plan on the weekend, which should be the largest in history.
This news was overshadowed by new concerns that the financial crisis was still far from over.
In the last chapter of the growing crisis, according to a government announcement on Monday, Citigroup is expected to buy the banking business of Wachovia Corporation.
Meanwhile, Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partially nationalized the European financial group Fortis.
According to analysts at Barclays Capital, despite the tense negotiations that took place over the weekend and led to a rescue plan, it appears that the mood in the markets has not been able to revive.
As the economic situation continues to deteriorate, it is expected that demand for goods, including oil, will continue to decline.
Analysts at Deutsche Bank wrote in a statement to investors that forecasts for global capital markets, interest rates and exchange rates had become extremely uncertain.
We believe they continue to write that the goods markets will also be affected.
“From the perspective of commodity markets, we are most concerned about whether the US virus is spreading worldwide, especially to China.”
