The pride and hardships in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden between the outgrowths of theme parks around Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, loud and gigantic bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first completely black town in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guava, 2 schools and no prison."
Today it is a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, the city she describes – and which made her a tourist destination by including her in the Florida guide, which was produced by the Federal Writers Project during the Depression – is in many ways a place of a very special kind.
Eatonville is so independent, dignified, and private as in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing."
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open conversation about racial relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
“We are very concerned about how our story is told,” says Hortense Jones, 59, from birth to a resident of the city and a parishioner of the oldest church in the city.
It has to be right."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of almost 2,400 inhabitants, where the poverty rate is twice as high as the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other hand, an example of the - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and on the hat.
And rightly so, the concerns about Eatonville's image actually began with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in oral art, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1973)
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Freckled like Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the shop of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Aside the road to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-white painted modern school, with its well-kept gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, although he can hardly read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sold drinks of any kind and what-even-always fits into hourly rooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by everyone.
"Zora described things as they were," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston, citing the men who sang songs about her beauty that were full of sexual allusions.
She added, “Some people don’t like this.”
One still remembers Hurtson as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembered that when Hurston came into town, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants, in a city that even today imagines something of her venerable style of clothing.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, while many despised them.
"People were always happy to see Zora," Mr Franklin said.
But "she never stayed too long," he added while swinging in his chair, on a rear facing terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, in which Hurston was probably baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary long-sister Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville there was no great commemoration, no public readings in the grand style.
“I don’t think they understood their contribution in the world or their legacy in the least,” said Valerie Boyd, author of “Wrapped in Rainbows,” a 2003 biography about Hurston.
The turn came in the 80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to lay a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the slow two-lane main street of the community.
Orlando’s suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult phase in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
“At this time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting away,” Mr. Franklin said.
“There was even a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car.”
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court’s demand to enforce integration by calling its decision against the school council in Brown’s case “insulting rather than respecting my race.”
Residents today say that although the repeal of racial segregation was positive in some respects, it weakened the group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
“Black children were used to being embraced — I remember — one embraced his teacher in the morning and one embraced his teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and managing director of the non-profit group to protect the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained for so long, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You didn't hug his white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural divide there," Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have contributed to the creation of space for other Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors, and artists who disregarded prejudice, as they did, with positive self-confidence and statements such as, "How can anyone deny the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker set out on her way to Hurston’s nameless grave and began to fight for the resurgence of her fame.
Five years later, a highly acclaimed Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway was to be found in the bookshelves, and once again made them part of the American literary canon.
The long-distance road project came at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans of a five-lane long-distance road revived the city, accelerated it at top speed, aroused real citizen pride," said Nathiri.
Mrs. Boyd put it a little easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the long-distance road project has contributed to a change in the self-image of the city.
There were more and more train trips, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville was incorporated into the national historical register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still a special feature in Florida: only 6 miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It is 90% black today.)
Outsiders looking for the history of Eatonville and its importance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, prior approval is necessary and certain things - such as the mural of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in fieldwork - may not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Mrs. Jones, a courageous, self-confident teacher with a fondness for dark red, still fear that their shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time as the Hurston Festival grew larger, an increased degree of domestic pride was also born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw their entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better and just as proud, creative and diligent, silly and intertwined as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love of this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who intends to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or in the police force who, according to him, might need some help.
And even the younger ones, such as Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to correctly describe Eatonville.
“Most people who only go through here will think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,’” Alondra Kenon said on a Sunday after the church.
"But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it's a very beautiful city."
