Interview - From the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, she regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross blood donation service were contaminated with the HI virus and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, in the face of this drama and public dissatisfaction, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation led by Judge Horace Krever aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and drafting guidelines to prevent another disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to submit his report, several provinces set up a committee at the time, whose goal was to develop a new system for the management of blood cans in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this task.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
<0x60>1998, when Hema-Quebec took up her work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood preservation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was disheartening.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood cans and through work in this field over the following years, we have regained public confidence,” she says, before proudly stressing that by the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted in accordance with the principle of caution.
At this time, we witnessed the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of bovine insanity in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
“And we didn’t have the slightest idea whether this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we came up with one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which states that exclusion measures are applied if one does not know this and if a disease progresses only slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999 no blood was taken from persons who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago it was proven without any doubt that this disease is transmitted via the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution we applied has quite a meaning.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST) that allow to detect the presence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation period, which takes place between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize this, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
In other words, it means that you would have to distribute 12 million blood cans before someone was infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cans each year, it would take more than 24 years for a case to occur where HIV was transmitted via a blood can.
I believe that today you can feel comfortable when you get a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore health,” says Hema-Quebec’s director.
“Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogens can enter the system.
Only last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted via the blood by insects.
We have to monitor continuously," Dr. Décary continues, before she stresses that Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate care in addition to a safe supply.
“The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
Because cancer control treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donation network, which on average includes only 3% of Quebec’s people eligible for blood donation.
Any healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who make their blood available are not accepted because, for example, they have become ill with AIDS or malaria, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria has spread are excluded from blood donation for one year.
“With these 3%, we manage to get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It’s hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to keep them and make them become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour giving blood,” Francine Décary laments.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec delivers not only blood canned but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which are used almost exclusively in severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being temporarily stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec’s only public cord blood bank.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered biomedical waste, there is rich blood in stem cells that can help treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
A few weeks ago, we celebrated the storage of our thousands of umbilical cord blood samples, and we plan to lose more than a thousand each year.
“We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year,” explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of umbilical cord blood loss as very popular.
“Many mothers are convinced they don’t have access to it,” because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
