The prime minister, however, was limited to explaining why the North was “a jewel with enormous potential,” but did not mention a date, investment sums, or exact priorities for the upcoming projects.
At most, some prospects for what could be worked on: especially on water energy, on the forest, but especially on the mining sector, favoured by the growth of emerging markets and the renewal of public infrastructures.
According to Mr. Charest's account, the north has nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium and even diamonds.
This 'area twice as large as France' is near us, is in Quebec.
It is not only near us, it is within us,' he stressed, as to show clearly that he is seeking to realize a national founding dream.
Quebec has grown greatly due to its connection with the north, he stressed: the road to gold in Abitibi, Quebec’s technology, the James Bay.
"It belongs to us, it's our future," he added after taking a theatrical break to look at the huge map behind him.
The north, 70% of the Quebec area, includes part of Labrador, which Quebec has always called for, the prime minister told the press.
“This is a traditional attitude that all governments followed.
There is a border line where there has been no agreement for a very long time, when the opportunity arises I will take this stance again on behalf of the government," he said.
“With climate change, we need to rethink our vision of the North,” he said, talking about the Northwest Passage, which will be accessible all year round due to the ice melt.
Against this new geopolitical background, the Prime Minister believes that it is precisely a duty to occupy this area.
And the inhabitants of the land, the natives and the Inuit?
The prime minister said the Quebec government would be very careful with them and that they would benefit from this project, especially the boys.
Two former ministers of various parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former Peculiar Member of Ungava) have already started consultations with some thirty communities.
A committee of ministers led by Beno<0xC3><0xAE>t Pelletier, in which Julie Boulet (transport and mineral resources) occupies an important place, has taken up the work.
The prime minister does not rule out a large assembly, not necessarily a summit, but an opportunity where ‘a common vision will be created’.
The development of the North will also be in line with the principles of sustainable development.
The North Plan will be 'discussed, regulated and environmentally friendly', he promised.
Jean Charest described this “vision” as a continuation of those of the liberal prime ministers who were in office before him.
“Like the liberals who were in office before us, we have turned the challenges into new growth and development opportunities.
This was, by the way, one of the recurring themes of the weekend, which opened on Friday with a large cocktail party to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the takeover of the party leadership by Jean Lesage.
One of the adopted resolutions envisages renaming the Beauharnois power plant in Adélard-Godbout-Staudamm.
“From Godbout, who created Hydro-Quebec, through Lesage, who achieved the silent revolution and nationalization of water electricity, to Bourassa, who made the James Bay, our party always knew how to determine the future,” said Jean Charest.
In front of the press, he referred to another, this time conservative, project, namely the program 'Roads to the North' by John Diefenbaker, Prime Minister from 1957 to 1963.
Regarding the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydropower dam project, Mr Charest stressed that its commissioning was planned for 2012.
