Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice General Director of the Canadian Barrick Gold Mine.
This confirms, and in doing so pursues an Orwellian logic that the world’s largest gold-winning company was seeking a defamation lawsuit over six million against three authors and a small, mediocre publishing house, with the aim of opening a ‘public transparent debate’.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge the truth, especially not in the case of defamation lawsuits, but the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to have a public debate is to ruin everyone who dares to represent one of their opposite opinions.
No matter how the process goes, the authors and editors of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defenses and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid out of the nearly inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactics of these unequal struggles, by the way, are often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual arrangement that makes the opposite mouth-to-mouth and also deters anyone who dares to deal with the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things to public opinion.
In contrast, what is common in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works is in Canada debates are usually carried out through the exchange of ideas and not by button strokes.
So it would have sufficed if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened up a real debate, through which newspapers, media, publications and the financing of independent audit teams could have brought light to this question.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have any confidence in public opinion, wiping aside the petitions and letters supporting the authors of Noir Canada with a hand movement.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can at the same time ask for a 'public' debate and yet disregard the opinions of this particular public?
Apparently, in the world of the Vice President, this word includes only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a quite narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand — or doesn’t want to understand — is that the public, who supports Noir Canada’s authors and publishers, is doing so primarily because it rejects the brutal stance of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a gag complaint (in the course of the ‘public debate’, Barrick Gold has just raised a demand for the authors of Noir Canada, in which she asks them not to use this term anymore...).
Apart from Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s lawsuit is a direct attack on freedom of academic research and truth-finding, which are fundamental to any democratic society.
It totally denies the right to cite credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to explore and discuss topics that the rich companies of this world do not like, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The university environment we belong to has long been able to handle debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, unlike what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for public debate, and it’s time for governments to take action to limit this kind of unjustified lawsuit.
Rescue for Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans understand each other
The Bush administration and senior congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most comprehensive economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new $700 billion plan to stop the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months still needs to be adopted by the two chambers of Congress.
The main content is: better control of MEPs over the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to secure the repayment of the public funds used, new arrangements to reduce the number of houses pledged due to payment defaults, and the right to monitor the salaries paid to the senior employees of the supported companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, the president of the Chamber of Deputies Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative present at the negotiations, Senator Judd Gregg, announced yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, the good news, after a two-day negotiation marathon.
“We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the market,” said the Bush administration’s representative, Henry Paulson.
“Everything happened to protect the real economy and the American people from the price crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“This is the fundamental point: if we don’t do this, the trauma, the chaos and the turmoil in Americans’ daily lives will be enormous,” Republican Judd Gregg said.
The negotiations had accelerated over the last two hours, fearing the effect that would have had a further failure on the mood of investors.
The deadline agreed was the opening of the market this morning.
The two American presidential candidates, who took part in the negotiations only late, were more likely to show themselves as supporters of the agreement, but without failing to express their discontent at the fact that they had to be met in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama insisted on the addition of certain arrangements for agreement, especially those designed to allow owners to keep their homes, and those relating to the salaries of senior employees of state-saved businesses.
“If you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain people, that’s nothing to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary," he explained on the American television channels.
When asked on another station if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied, “I would like to know the details first, but I hope so.
The guiding principles that I have read [show] that this is one thing that we will all have to digest, and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan is aimed at making money from taxpayers
It comes 14 months after a crisis, triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble, which first led to the collapse of the high-risk mortgage loans (subprime) before it expanded to further forms of more widely used bonds (PCAA), and finally culminated in a freeze of financial power and the ruin of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican MPs who failed the first attempt to reach an agreement last week.
Since the Democrats have accepted that certain “toxic” assets of societies should only be secured in distress by the government and not bought, the dead end is believed to be avoided.
To round off the perspectives for everyone in Congress, one has also added an order stating that if the government should make losses with this program within five years, it could then raise new taxes in order to recover its invested capital.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of 250 billion, to which an additional 100 billion can be added if the president sees it as necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion must be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In return for his help, Washington gains shares in the supported companies that bring him dividends in the event of profits, and which it can resell once the storm has passed.
The Federal Government will have the opportunity to stop the attachment proceedings relating to the apartments linked to the real estate loans affected by this plan, and also to set deadlines for the repayment and redemptions paid to the senior employees of the companies concerned.
The developers of the plan would like the Chamber of Deputies to vote on him today, and then the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get green light.
In fact, there were further votes against this plan yesterday, both by the Republicans and the Democrats.
“Clearly Washington doesn’t understand us,” Republican Scott Garett, a member of the Chamber’s Financial Commission, told voters.
“Yes, we have a big financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not those who are in the process of asking the taxpayers to cash in."
Democratic MP Brad Sherman, head of a group in Congress called the “Caucus of the Skeptics,” presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred excellent economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to tell us: We ask Congress not to be pressured, and carefully consider which way to go,” he said.
At the same time, we in Europe were once again given the proof that this is a global crisis.
At an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the banking group Fortis for €11.2 billion ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it would refrain from buying up its competitor, who is in great difficulty since losing 2 billion euros (US$2.9 billion) in the crisis due to the high-risk real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the 20 largest European banks and the 10 largest insurers.
"This is not a lost money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
To compensate, we receive a right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what the savers and households appreciate, now that uncertain times are coming.”
During this time, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government was in the process of nationalizing another bank in distress from the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all current loans from Bank Bradford and Bringley, of which over 41 billion (75.5 billion US dollars) from real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy up the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank to nationalize the UK government since the start of the financial crisis.
