The Psychology of Overbidity – or Why We Are Ready to Pay More
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overestimate the error bid.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the “Science” magazine, people don’t want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even overpriced prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was supposed to play the lottery while the other took part in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by means of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured in the case of losers of the auction, in which the overbiding of the opponent plays an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to substantiate their thesis, the economists in the research group have additionally carried out investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised $15 reward in case they emerge as winners from the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in case of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was that the emphasis on one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "against losing" group were ready for higher stakes than those in the control or "winning" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have so far only justified the behaviour observed at auctions with the joy of winning, or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation ready," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected in this country is estimated to be one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
Symptoms are often similar – inflammation of the liver and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in the case of hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water), in the case of hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, secretion of vagina or saliva).
Travellers are advised to vaccinate against viruses A and B anyway, there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A show up about two to three weeks after consuming the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, the jaundice appears on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the recovery can last up to two or three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from hepatitis B-induced, far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten people infected is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms show up after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who had undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooists.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the GP at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognised in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, which eliminates the risk of infection and prevents the development of cancer.
September 30th is the World Day of Hepatitis, first held in 2004 by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of this chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, their emergence and the importance of early detection.
