Intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop new technologies to avoid accidents, if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, bees.
At the CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented that inspired the Nissan engineers of bumblebees in creating new accident avoidance systems.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C autobotter-controlled biomimetic system, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective shield", Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, said at the exhibition.
The compound eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles before the BR23C in a field of view of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is registered in fractions of a second, and the autobot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
"If it were not so, the autobot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the autobot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered unavoidable.
The entire process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they avoid other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, avoidance cannot be done up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the reversibility of the tires.
While the bees here are open to endless possibilities to avoid other bees, the researchers at the auto-robot could only use the rotary movement, or the acceleration and braking.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer service life than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only has to process a few inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It does not have to store these, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction on the basis of previous maneuvers, so that it constantly takes only a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately directing the driver around obstacles and thus guiding him to the destination.
