Tests carried out with different materials such as glass Teflon and sandpaper have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the durability of the feet of the reptiles and at the same time allows "problemless removal from the wall", according to Liming Dai, a researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
"This material could be used as a perishable adhesive," Liming Dai adds.
Perhaps, but the researchers are more likely to think of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also the conductors of heat and electricity.
Other areas of application may fall within the space sector.
For the moment, the superheroes still have to wait.
