In an article by the American Chemical Society, Californian scientists present a microfiber adhesive that, like hair, cleans itself from dust by moving on a surface and thus always maintains a perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These beverages, which are consumed in summer due to their refreshing quality and vitamin richness, can cause serious health damage if taken at the same time with certain vital medicines, since they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points to the risk of packaged as well as fresh fruit juices in conjunction with medication intake. As part of the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again raised an alarm: A glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is sufficient to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital medicines to the extent that they are virtually limped in health.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected to be responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, up to toxic levels.
Medications in Danger – The same agency of the drug had warned doctors and patients about the dangers of this mixture in a report two years ago, stressing to watch out for what is drunk in conjunction with drugs such as diazepan or methadone.
It’s not just GRAPEFRUT – According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active substances inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Therefore, Michele Carruba, director of the Universit<0xC3><0xA0> Statale di Milano, said: "These results are usually immediately forwarded to the various international manufacturers, who are thus free to change consumer information.
Therefore, it is recommended to always read the package leaflet and, if there is any ambiguity, not to be afraid to ask a pharmacist or doctor,” emphasizes the expert of the Ansa Agency.
Nobel Prize goes to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize is awarded to the American Paul Krugman for his analysis of trade patterns and the settlement of economic activities.
The 55-year-old Krugman is a Neokeynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is known for his regular articles for the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration’s economic and foreign policy.
A few months after the September 11, 2001 attacks, during the days of the Enron collapse, Krugman had claimed in a New York Times editorial that this second event was more crucial to the history of the United States than the assassinations.
A prediction that did not receive little polemics in response and was held to the economist years later, but proved to be absolutely correct today.
"I am surprised and also shocked at how quickly the memory of the scandals disappeared from the public eye as part of the collapses of Enron or Worldcom," Krugman said at the end of 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is an "economist of great value", but also a banaliser with a "very aggressive style, which is particularly directed against the excessive liberalism of the Bush administration."
Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package will be released
The day of publication of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the Open Source Software wins as a free replacement for Microsoft’s Office an increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in public administration.
After a year of intensive work by the volunteer developers, which is monitored by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office now presents itself to the public with some novelties: in addition to a revised and now more spartanly designed initial menu, now finally a guaranteed compatibility with Apple’s Mac OS x operating system has been achieved, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, i.e. the latest version of the Open Document Format.
It also noted compatibility with Microsoft Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Also interesting are some new features, such as those that allow to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which makes it easier, for example, to send via email. This also includes the possibility of importing PDF files into graphics editing modules and at the same time preserving the original appearance of the page.
Thus, hybrid PDF files can now also be generated, which extend the typical graphics of the Adobe format to the elements of a table and a word processing system.
Collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be edited by multiple users, avoiding conflicts in the event of changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a question to guarantee a better correction procedure.
Some companies are just about to publish various features of OpenOffice on the Internet (on the cloud), while the final result will be made public in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download at the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. Thus, it follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
Except for Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, you can have the installation CD sent to your home or office.
However, if cost-freeness can be an incentive for the distribution of the program in private households, it is also in the business sector where OpenOffice could succeed in the big throw: after all, various public administration and schools institutions have already moved to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of a training offer, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word corresponding text creation program; Calc, the table program that aims to displace Excel; Impress, for creating presentations such as PowerPoint; Dbase for running databases instead of the more familiar Access; and finally Draw, a graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to achieve 5 million downloads – a goal that can be easily exceeded with already reached 3 million and 600 thousand.
