Farewell to the old Paradiso cinema – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historical cinemas close due to the favored multiplex cinemas.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
This image of the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, means in the long run the death of the single-room cinema in the center, a process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the traits of a cultural crime.
“It’s like losing a friend with whom you’ve covered a piece of street full of emotions,” says the director of the film “Nuovo Cinema Paradiso”, who brought him the Oscar and the Grand Prix of Cannes 20 years ago. It’s the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is probably lost forever.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these works mostly paid for the cinemas in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions include Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This proves that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," said Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "although it is useful that new structures also arise, but the first priority is the preservation of what already exists, because if a hall in the city closes, not all of its regular customers are ready to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here the lack of budget for the fund of the trade association remains to be seen: the debt burden recorded by the state amounts to about 10 million euros.
It is a shame from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not comply with existing laws.
To maintain the sector would be between 16 and 18 million euros per year of distress".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, due to the fears surrounding the old cinemas, has decided to protect it by an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first such agreement in Italy aimed at protecting and supporting traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the measures envisaged are tax benefits for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be allowed to drive to the traffic restricted areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
“It’s a pleasing initiative,” said Giuseppe Tornatore, “I hope that other cities will join our example and also design new concepts.
But certainly we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to do something against the superpower of the multiplex rooms, because after all, today’s audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of Baghiera’s “Supercinema”, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the “Nuovo cinema Paradiso”, even though I had been playing with my mind for 10 years.
For 25 years I have been living in Rome; when I pass by the Rialto or Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side so as not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
