When the energy comes out of the waves, the big ones suddenly run up.
It is a non-depleting source of money that covers over 70% of the planet’s surface and only now seems to understand this the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that all now look at, and also seek to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years; not by chance, these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, the idea of marine energy was gassed, but now the environmental organizations and the increased price of oil are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world’s energy demand could be covered by the energy generated by the ocean waves.
This would be equal to twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there were also currents and tides.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract to build a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are now relying on marine energy production.
“Chevron is investigating these technologies,” said the spokesperson of a company known to the American giant in the Wall Street Journal, and is considering the possibility of working with us.
This is about obtaining an approval from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is needed to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially considering that oil is still being promoted by the United States in Alaska, and President Bush recently set in motion plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, New York-based Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey-based Ocean Power are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, observers are talking about an increasing interest.
Even better technologies.
Experts speak of a technology that is still in its infancy, not least because the last doubts have not yet been clarified by environmentalists.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of rather small dimensions and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, it requires technologies with far greater impact on the environment.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the shafts, which move the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater pipelines.
So far, there are four planned installations of this kind, which are only waiting for state approval. Part of the energy obtained could also serve military facilities.
However, Verdant Power already produces energy for a department store and a parking lot using submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator as a result of the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
A particular interest, according to the Institute for Power Generation Research, is currently deserving of the potential that lies in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is precisely tidal energy that led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest up to $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are planned for 2009.
